WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:24.000
Today is Monday April 25, 2011. My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Oral History Program.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:34.000
I'm here in collaboration with the National Museum of African American History and Culture in Atlanta, Georgia.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Good afternoon. Good afternoon. It's a pleasure to be with you. It's a pleasure to be with you too.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:53.000
We are here for an interview in the museum series on civil rights history, although as we have touched on in our comments before we started today,

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:59.000
we may talk about even that phrase and its relation to history with us today.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Miss Sails, thank you so much and let's start if we could. I'm interested to have you reflect a little bit about your father and mother.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:15.000
I noticed in my preparation that you described at one point your father is having somewhat radicalized by the (Korean) War experience.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Yes. But also, of course, probably in the exchange that's growing up happening and you met in South Alabama and you can visit your head.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:27.000
So, in fact, in your mother too was someone who would be more useful in public context in certain things?

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Yes. You said she knew a question about the fact.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Well, let's begin with my father. My father was the son of a woman who was either born in slavery, an enslavement, or immediately after.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:55.000
We don't know how, but she learned how to read and write. She was a teacher and valued education very much.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:08.000
And met my grandfather who we think came down South from Virginia through the migration after the Civil War and ended up in the LaGrange, Georgia.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:17.000
And moved from the LaGrange, Georgia to Birmingham to Birmingham and throughout that area as an itinerant preacher.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:23.000
And he married my grandmother who had 13 children and my father was one of those children.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:36.000
And my father joined First Assisi (Civilian Conservation) Camp and then later joined the Army and was also ordained as a Baptist minister and functioned as a chaplain in the Army.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:49.000
And was very much insightful in terms of the contradiction between being in the Army and having to live in a segregated and racist society.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Not only that he was a highly intelligent man who talks with us constantly about the issues of World War II.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:11.000
So I grew up knowing about Port Chicago. I grew up knowing about the Big Three and so my father, what I'm really trying to say is that my father gave to us a world that has some context and meaning.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:25.000
And within that world, race figured largely. And he was very much active in raising the question during the Korean War about black men dying on foreign soil when they could not.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:47.000
Vote at home and my mother having grown up a very hard economic reality having to fin for herself developed a certain characteristic in a certain strength that prevailed in all that she did and she was not someone to be passive.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:59.000
She was not someone to submit to oppression lightly. We didn't want to go downtown with her ever because if someone in the store disrespected her, it was going to be a scene.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
So we didn't want to go with her.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:10.000
Yes, a white person who would disrespect her in stores, she would definitely have a lot to tell them about what they had done.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:18.000
And of course, being self-conscious as young people, we just were totally embarrassed.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.000
You also with extendication, some of that I understand in general.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:24.000
Yes, which is where my grandmother lived.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.000
Tell me about that experience.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:33.000
Well, that experience was a very important experience for me on another level that gave my life context.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:41.000
I would say if without exaggerating, 30% of that town were sales and were my relatives.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:49.000
And I could go to the cemetery and see generations of sales laid out in the cemetery.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:54.000
And in addition to that, I had uncles and aunts and cousins.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
So I was a part of a large extended family.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:04.000
And I knew the history of that family.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:09.000
And I also began to see myself in relationship to my aunts. Let me tell you what I mean.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Somebody would say you're just like your aunt Nian.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Or somebody would say that you're just like your aunt Ray.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:23.000
So I had some, and so all of my life, I saw myself as a sales, rather than as a fletcher, which is what my mother was a fletcher.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:28.000
I was always a sales and temperament and looks.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:34.000
And in a love for knowledge, my father was very, very smart.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:43.000
He had fought for a while in the Second War and then the Korean War.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:52.000
But the Second War was a little bit different because people really felt like they were fighting for democracy in a very different kind of way than they felt during the Korean War.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:55.000
So that was a little bit different for him.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:02.000
You also spoke about your experiences in something of a normal world and a child.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:03.000
Yes.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:13.000
Given that your father's NCO status in economy meant that you had certain experiences on base that were not then replicated in the civil society.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:21.000
Yes. Once we left Columbus, Georgia, which is about 10 miles from Fort Benning, we could ride on the front of the bus or anywhere.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:26.000
We wanted to ride because of Truman's integration of the Army.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:31.000
And in addition to that, we could go to movie theaters, integrated movie theaters.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:43.000
We could go to integrated restaurants and we could go to an integrated, integrated hospital where the doctors were white and very different from Southern white doctors.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:49.000
But for all of that, it sounds as if you were a normal company.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:56.000
It sounds as if you're real awakening to your active consciousness about race and...

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:59.000
That doesn't happen really until you're a little bit older.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:02.000
No, it does not on a real conscious level.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:06.000
But it is operating. This is how it's operating.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:18.000
I don't have words for it. But my friends, we would go into department stores, a women's stores and ask to try on bathing suits.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:27.000
And we'd do things, and for example, we sat on the front of the bus, rang the buzzer, got out and started laughing and running.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:46.000
So in our very childish ways, I think a lot of children in the South will recount stories where they challenged the system without realizing what they were doing because intuitively we knew that there was something wrong with it and that it wasn't nice or fair to us.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
What kind of nature of your primary school and what you got at...

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:58.000
I started out at a Catholic high school called Mother Mary Mission because at that time my parents did not want me to go to a one-room school house.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:07.000
And then in the third grade in my neighborhood, which was Carver Heights, one of the first subdivisions in Columbus, Georgia.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:14.000
Principally because many of the men were affiliated with the military and got FHA loans.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:32.000
I then transferred to Carver High School, which was an incredible elementary school, where it was an all black elementary school with incredible teachers who really believed that we were capable of achieving our highest potential and pushed us to do it.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:40.000
And so my high school was like... my elementary school was like two blocks from my house. And so was my high school.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:46.000
And my high school was a training ground for citizenship, for creativity, and for scholarship.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:56.000
And my principal, S.P. Charleston and my home teacher, set the highest standards up for academic excellence.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:03.000
Although the world might have argued that black students were inferior, none of that touched us.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:07.000
Because we thought that we were leaders, we thought we were smart, and we thought...

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:15.000
We certainly thought that we were first class students. And so in many ways, they're gifts that they brought were two things.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:24.000
That they were able to insulate us from segregation in a way that kept us from being broken-wing birds.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:38.000
And the other thing that they did that was really a tremendous gift, is that they had the capacity to keep on fertilizing the ground of education and building generations when there was no evidence that their work would bear fruit.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:47.000
And rather than approaching it from a despondent position, they were exuberant. The work meant everything.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:56.000
And the other thing that was very significant is that they connected young people with the project of freedom that we had enrolled in that.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:07.000
And our role was not just to get an education for our own career advancement, but our role was to get an education to play a role in moving forward the entire community.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:25.000
So you had the considerable advantage of this kind of experience with parents as you described with the elementary school settings as encouraging someone you did.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
I have, yes please.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:43.000
And a culture that took pride in our achievements and a culture of people who themselves were deeply invested in the process so that there was a connection between what our parents did and what the neighbors did.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:57.000
And they saw the school as part of a collective investment. They literally created a counterculture education where right in the glare of segregation, they managed to create good schools and good students.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:03.000
When you were, how did you, what were your social crowds as a high school?

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:14.000
I have to confess I was in the end crowd. I was a cheerleader. I had a lot of mouth for a young girl.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:24.000
I was an editor of the newspaper in the Honor Society. Pretty well known, not only in my school, but throughout the community.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:35.000
So I would say that I had a very, very busy social life, very connected social life. And I would also say that I was pretty much a rebel.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
I challenged some of the rules and got away with it.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:50.000
And then why would it be because of who you were as a young person or because also your parents were or because your teachers were savvy enough to let you have some of that space?

00:11:50.000 --> 00:12:00.000
Because my home teacher was one of the most powerful teachers at the school. And also because they recognized that beyond my rebelliousness, I had something worth cultivating.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:08.000
And they didn't want to rain me in too much to break my spirit. And so that was one of another reason why I was allowed to rebel.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:17.000
And I think that they knew that rebellion was a substance of survival. And they didn't want us to accommodate this aggregation.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:27.000
They didn't want us to get killed, but they didn't want us to accommodate. And I think also it was because I belong to a family who was thought to have the smartest kids in Columbus.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:33.000
So I think all of that played a great role in what I was allowed to do.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:39.000
You moved at a very young age and sort of measured by today's standards, I guess, towards Tuskegee Institute.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:43.000
Yes. Why, how do you came to shift there at such young age in 1963?

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:50.000
Because there was a program throughout the South that if you could pass a test, you could go to school at a very early age.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:13:02.000
Some people went at 14, 15, and 16 years old. And I went at 16 years old. And I went to Tuskegee Institute because my home teacher, Marian Armstrong, went to Tuskegee Institute.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:09.000
I had some notion in my rebellion state that I would go to college first. I would go to the Army.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:18.000
Well, that was a delusious, first of all, I wasn't old enough. Secondly, when my mother found out about it, she went right down to the recruiting office and reminded them that I wasn't old enough.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:28.000
And then I thought I'd go to Drake University. And I would. Well, that was also a fantasy. And I ended up going to Tuskegee Institute.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:41.000
Tell me about the experience of landing at Tuskegee Institute in the fall of 1963, because obviously the early 1960s have been tumultuous.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:48.000
I think there's so many respects in the United States around the race and other issues, especially race and course.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:54.000
And you arrived at a time when there was a awful lot happening in Alabama?

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:12.000
Yes. The movement in Alabama resonates at Tuskegee Institute when I get there. As a matter of fact, Gwen Patton, who becomes a president of the student body, was part of the Montgomery Boycott and had been around the movements and she was a young child.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:25.000
She brought two Tuskegee Institute movement consciousness. In addition to that, Professor (Charles) Gomillion had been involved in challenging Jeremandering in Tuskegee Institute.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:36.000
So Tuskegee Institute already had built there when we got there an atmosphere of protest and movement.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:57.000
And our dean, Dean Phillips, encouraged us to be involved in the movement, unlike many deans. And so when Gwen Patton asked the student, let me just go back a moment to say that when I first arrived at Tuskegee Institute, I did not choose to be a part of the movement.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:05.000
I wanted to be a beatnik. And so I was running around Tuskegee Institute trying to be a beatnik.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:22.000
Drinking wine at the local pun, hanging out, you know, quoting poetry, Allen Ginsberg. And so I did not have any thought of being in the movement because I had built my life around Virginia Woolf and had built my life around Greenwich Village in my head.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:32.000
And so Tuskegee Institute was just a road, a penance I had to do before I could go to the village. And so that was not in my mind.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:46.000
And so Stokely Carmichael came to campus. And people from Lowndes County came to campus and they gave a rousing conversation about the importance of participating in the movement.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:54.000
And it was at that moment that I became galvanized and I became interested in the movement. And so I threw away my guitar pink.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:16:15.000
I cut my ponytails and I began to grow natural hair. And I went down to Lowndes County, Alabama. But that was not until after we had the demonstration students at Tuskegee Institute in protest for the beatings that had occurred on the Edmund Pettus Bridge.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:32.000
And we were locked in at the Capitol in Montgomery, surrounded by, you know, you have to understand this is a new experience surrounded by men with Billy Clubs, horse men on horses.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:46.000
And so I was just, wouldn't let us go to the bathroom. And yes, these are features of segregation, but you have to understand that as students we had not come up against that because our parents had made the soul so safe.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:17:01.000
And I don't know how they did it, but they did. So this what I'm trying to say is that that day shook my life when the horses started charging and the men and those white men started swinging the Billy Clubs.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:13.000
And I tell you, I was so naive, I'm almost ashamed to admit this, that I kept looking up in the sky because I had grown up with this notion of God or the mighty chariot delivering God's children.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:25.000
And if you were doing the right thing, then you would be delivered. And I waited and waited and waited and waited in no chariot and no God. And that day I lost my southern Baptist religion.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:45.000
And I went into contextualized the world beyond theological terms, looking for social and economic terminologies to explain the world. So I would say, and it was in that setting that I saw the power of nonviolence when antipyral every one of the SNCC women,

00:17:45.000 --> 00:18:01.000
and I saw the line to bring us food because we had no one could bring us food. The police would let no one come in the church. And I saw this little woman when the police raised his hand to hit her with the Billy Club.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:13.000
I saw her simply ask him, dead in the eyes, who are you going to hit? What are you going to do with that? And to my astonishment he dropped it and she came through the line.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:36.000
And so this time I little Columbus Georgia mind is blown. And so I was that at that moment very committed to moving forward. My home teacher Marian Armstrong drove 80 miles from Columbus, Georgia to ask me to leave the church because we had other and her other students who were in the church to leave.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:54.000
And I didn't and she said something like me, I should have known that you wouldn't have left. But that was a defining moment for me where I separated myself out from the approval of older adults about whether I should have should not be in the middle of that.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:19:03.000
And breaking into booze it meant going to a freedom house and being in the same sleeping in the same room with men.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:14.000
You are not having sex with but redefining the nature relationships between men and women that you could actually sleep in the bed with the men and not have sex.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:24.000
If there was something between men and women called comradeship and friendship. So we were breaking all kinds of boundaries by being in the freedom house.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:30.000
I have not done until this now understood that your active participation did start in the last place.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:33.000
Yes. This is spring 65.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:37.000
You've been a whole year semester that.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:45.000
Well, we've been no we haven't been watching because as I said, Gwen Patton is a part. And so she's been things have been happening on campus.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:54.000
Some of them I participated in and others I didn't and many of them had to do with talking with the community about what was going on in Selma.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:20:05.000
But my major commitment was not movement at that point. It wasn't that I wasn't doing things but that wasn't a commitment. I was a beatnik. I was not a freedom fighter.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:14.000
I think the more about your first encounter is my company to protest with a couple of things. One with you said it was really good.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:17.000
It really is kind of sweet way to communicate it.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:18.000
Yes.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:21.000
And violence and you don't.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:31.000
But also I imagine there must have been questions that emerged from the fact that you didn't get the warmest perception even at that time of that this church.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:39.000
I don't think it was questions. I think it was totally amazement.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:59.000
I think it went beyond asking questions to really being stunned and trying to make a connection to understand how these people who had been at the forefront of movement could lock us out of their church could want us to leave the church and not give us food.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:09.000
So yes, that happened. And at the same time I saw what happened is Stokely Carmichael reached the end of his limit at that period.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:17.000
And basically had a nervous breakdown in the Montgomery airport because of all the violence in his years of being on the siege.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:35.000
So many things were changing how I. But I was not angry with the deacons because there were the deacons. I was not angry with them because often because I guess I had been reared in an environment where you could question your elders.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:51.000
You could even not do what they say do, but you couldn't harbor a deep hate and anger. So I let it go because I had to do with them. I felt and very little to do with where I was going and seeing it that way.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:55.000
I did not hold any grudges against them and none of us did.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:22:03.000
Very quickly after a month, I only yielded within the space of three months.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:07.000
I want to ask a couple things.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:17.000
I never did. To be said, these were questions actively on your mind in that kind of cascading that I did with conditioning and we'll get to do those things in the moment over to Mount Scam.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:26.000
Your notion of yourself as a woman, young woman, you mentioned what happened. I know that also another context.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.000
Gomillion, your Tuskegee professor, yes.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:38.000
What are the very important focuses? Your sense of how perhaps was there a shift in evolution and development in your sense of yourself in the moment?

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:50.000
As I said that there had always been a perception of myself through the eyes of Southern Black women who were very busy on many fronts.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:23:02.000
But where the shift came for me in a very profound way was rethinking what is my role in life. Do I have to get married? Do I have to have 2.5 children?

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:11.000
How is it that I have a fashion life for myself that represents my horizon rims and where I'm headed?

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:31.000
In that way, I think how I moved in the world on that level as a woman began to really, really change and how I began to relate to men began to really, really change because men were, I began to see men as I said early, not merely through a boyfriend and girlfriend terms,

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:41.000
but through friendship terms and began to develop a deep trust in men because we worked together and had to depend on each other.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:57.000
So in a, in a, in a runnacle way as I was expanding my womanhood, I was also expanding how I saw men and in the value of men that I was not reducing them to a sexual object.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:05.000
After my gun, you had the first hand and pretty bad, not in town, with a lot of theater.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:20.000
And I wonder if, well, we have two questions that run together. One is, what do you think you were willing, you personally were willing to step forward and move towards Lowndes County?

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:34.000
And, and into an arena of such anxiety and active day-to-day worrying of fear of utter fear while they, why would you, why are some people willing to do it and others others are not?

00:24:34.000 --> 00:25:01.000
I think that I was willing to do it because as I said to you, my father spoke out against issues and my mother spoke out against issues and although her speaking out embarrassed me, it had a very profound impact on having me understand that I could defend myself.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:10.000
The other thing is I have such a big mouth in school that my principal would always say to me, you're going to be a great civil rights lawyer.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:20.000
There was always a connection between my mouth and the destinies of African-American people. That was another thing that had a profound impact on me.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:37.000
And the other thing is that I had a rebellious spirit. I was not happy being the typical teenager, being the typical college student. Those things bored me and I was in search for a larger meaning in life.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:54.000
And the civil rights movement, the Southern Freedom Movement gave me an opportunity to give voice to some of those, to some of the issues that I was struggling with.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:26:11.000
Let me just add to that. I had always seen myself as capable of doing exactly what men did in many ways because I was a champion marble player. I beat them at basketball.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:29.000
And so I never saw myself as being subservient. And that was an important part of the unwillingness to stand a small space, which was circumscribed to women. I did not want to be merely in that space.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:51.000
That, oh gosh, the date that was Jonathan was killed in 64, it was not 65. It was, it was months before Jonathan was killed.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:27:04.000
Yes. A little bit before the end of the school year. Yes. Yes. And I was once again while I'm growing, I'm naive.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:13.000
You have to understand that I didn't come from a hate field society. I didn't understand that people could hate you merely because you were black.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:27.000
I had an openness to the world that was devoid of violence. And it was repugnant to me to see anyone hurt another person.

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:48.000
And so to enter into this world where the first day we went to register people to vote, Stokely Carmichael, Mary Nell Mosley, my friend who had come with me from Tuskegee Institute, and we went down to the courthouse and the sheriff drew a gun to him and told him he would blow his fucking brains out".

00:27:48.000 --> 00:28:03.000
And Stokely said to him, well, hell will be an integrated hell tonight. And to see someone be able to stand up before a gun, not crying, not afraid, not backing down, touched me deeply.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:26.000
And cemented my determination to be a part of this spectacular movement with young people. And then I think what also startled me were the stories that were told by the local people about the violent history of Lowndes County about it being called Bloody Lowndes.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:42.000
I had met black people from the rural south because my grandmother lived there. But because they were my relatives, I didn't pay attention to their bravery in their hospitality.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:57.000
But in Lowndes County, I was moved by the hospitality and the bravery of the local people that they would share the little bit of food that they had with all of us. Mr. Jackson gave us a freedom house.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:10.000
Clara Mall, one of the young women in the county, risked her life driving us around Lowndes County all the way to Selman sometimes. And the community is graciousness.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:24.000
It's willingness to be with the threat of violence every day and to risk much more than I risk because they risked everything. The children, their houses, because they lived there.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:44.000
And I might have come to Lowndes County with some elitism, but I think that dissolved pretty rapidly. And I developed a lifelong respect for the capacity of ordinary people to do extraordinary things. And their willingness on the adverse circumstances to do it.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:30:09.000
Could you describe a day doing work in Lowndes County maybe you may know mostly what else. But that was like what we saw.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:27.000
We saw we would knock on doors, talk with people. And sometimes we saw poverty that was so extreme. We sometimes saw children who were hungry needed to be in school but had no shoes.

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:53.000
We saw men and women out in the fields, picking cotton and picking cucumbers. And we joined them to pick cucumbers. But I wasn't wanting to pick cotton. And we saw just a community living under the grind and the weight of segregation determined not to be terrorized or intimidated.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:31:07.000
And so we saw the community going about this normal business on the one hand, but on the other hand, taking care of the immediate and new question of freedom.

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:15.000
Did you feel that as those first several months went on, did you feel that you were making progress? Did it feel like a successful project?

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:25.000
I feel that I was making progress because it wasn't for me to make the progress. I saw the evolution of local people moving from where they had once been to where they were going.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:40.000
I saw them executing leadership in mass meetings. I saw them participating in the process of organizing their neighbors to bring them to the mass meetings. I saw them preparing food so that people could eat.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:57.000
I saw them not being afraid when the police would stop them. I saw them as we were forced to do chase out, outrun, pick up trucks of white men who were chasing us with guns.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:10.000
So I never felt it was my project. I never felt it was my goal to me. I always felt that we were in a collective process and that no individual drove the process.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:21.000
That there was room for everybody and everybody had to carry their weight. So I thought I was carrying my weight, but I certainly was ambled enough to know that it wasn't mine to define.

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:31.000
Miss, can you tell me a little bit more in a picture of Mrs. McBill or Mr. Jackson or (John) Hulett or Clara Maul?

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:46.000
Well, I met (John) Hulett. I thought he was one of the bravest men I've ever seen. You have to understand that I came from a community where I had never seen an uneducated black man in leadership position.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:54.000
That in our community to be in that kind of leadership position usually was was reserved for college graduates.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:33:09.000
And (John) Hulett was the first person I saw in that kind of position who did not have an education. And the other thing about (John) Hulett, that really struck me, was that every time he said he would be there he showed up.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:17.000
That was very, very important. Keeping one's word in such violent circumstances.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:26.000
Clara Maul was like a wild stallion in a very good sense. She could drive 100 miles an hour, which she often did when we were being...

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:30.000
I'm sorry.

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:36.000
Okay. Can I have you make that a point you did about (John) Hulett specifically in relation to...

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:38.000
He was always there when he said he would be there.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:42.000
He was always there when he said it would be. And he was not a man...

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:52.000
Who's a man that the spot light? He was not a man who insisted on holding the microphone and not letting anyone else speak.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:34:00.000
He was in many ways at the height of his sincerity.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:11.000
And I came to trust and rely on him. And we had a connection. His sister had taught me in high school. So we had that little connection.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:18.000
I thought he was the right person at that particular time.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:20.000
I'm not Clara Maul.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:25.000
Clara Maul was my friend in addition to being a woman who lived in the county.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:33.000
And I often spent the night with them at their house and she was married with three children. But she had an absolute commitment to the movement.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:37.000
And she and I would do very daring things.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:42.000
Going to areas to register people to vote where we probably shouldn't have gone.

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:48.000
And she was always there with food. Her grandmother had had...

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:56.000
Was having a lifetime liaison with one of the richest white men in the county. And she owned a bar.

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:02.000
And so Clara Maul was off limits to local white mobs.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:06.000
And so she could tear through the county and do anything she wanted to.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:11.000
And if you were with Clara, you were well protected. And the bar was off limit.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:17.000
And so we would gather at the bar because a grandmother owned with some Friday night recreation.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:21.000
Clara was very important. Even stoke they relied on her.

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:26.000
Clara was very important to the movement. Stop.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:30.000
And Clara was beautiful.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:39.000
And I looked up to her quite frankly because of her beauty, her courage, her commitment, and her willingness

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:47.000
to do what needed to be done, even at the cost of possibly being hurt.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:52.000
And she played an important role in the movement.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:57.000
I think the Johnson signing of the Voting Rights Act, in the 6th of August.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:03.000
And it was just a week after I guess it was going to be a four-time positive.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:11.000
How did you know about how that, how that, how that, that that was, I came to the end because I know it was a little weird.

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:20.000
The young people, the young people in Fort Deposit whose parents worked on plantations and were forced to shop at the local store.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:29.000
And because of this, they were often cheated and never realized any profit from the work that they had done all year.

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:37.000
And the young people, the young black people were angry as seeing their parents being cheated.

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:43.000
Not only being angry, they were on fire with movement spirit.

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:48.000
And they wanted to play a role in changing things.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:52.000
Not only for their parents, but for Alabama, for the nation.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:37:01.000
And they suggested they brought to us a plan where they wanted to do a demonstration.

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:08.000
And SNCC did not want to do that demonstration.

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:17.000
But how do you tell young people who are organizing and stepping forth for the first time?

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:23.000
How can you squelch their spirit and say don't do it?

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:32.000
The reason why we didn't want to do it is that to be perfectly honest, we were frightened because not, of what the deposit was just a nightmare.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:39.000
And so we had a great SNCC debate that went on for hours and hours to talk about what we would do.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:48.000
And a part of that debate hinged on the question of Jonathan's participation, Jonathan and Father (Richard) Morrisroe's participation.

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:59.000
And Stokeley very much wanted to keep the movement open to whosoever wanted to come, let them come.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:07.000
He did not want to close out despite the dangers of black and white together in Lowndes County.

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:11.000
He did not want to close out the possibility of Johns participating.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:14.000
And by then they had become friends.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:19.000
I was among the people who said no.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:22.000
I said I thought it was true, dangerous.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:29.000
I said that I thought it would jeopardize what we were trying to do.

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:38.000
And of course Stokeley's voice and Jonathan's voice who argued vociferously his position won the day.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:47.000
And I ended up feeling if you're going to segregate the movement, then why are we here?

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:55.000
So I went over to their position after really thinking about the arguments, the genuine arguments that were being made,

00:38:55.000 --> 00:39:08.000
not grandstanding arguments, not exploitive arguments, but genuine arguments that came from democratizing the movement and holding to that vision of democratization.

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:21.000
So having made that decision, we all participated in the demonstration, which took place on Saturday morning.

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:33.000
And when we got there, it was one of the most frightening things I've ever seen.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:38.000
There was a mob of white men there.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:41.000
And I guess being a mob, you're undisciplined.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:48.000
And they had ever conceivable weapons, baseball bats, garbage pills, anything it seemed that they could lay their hands on.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:50.000
They had.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:56.000
And they were threatening to beat us up, kill us.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:40:07.000
And as the day, as the time wore on, they were getting louder and less willing to hold back the violence that they threatened to unleash.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:25.000
And I think I'm not sure that we were probably arrested, not only because they did not approve of what we were doing, but also somewhere I think that they realized that if they didn't get us out of there, we were going to get killed.

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:34.000
So by the day I mean the white officials, we were put on a garbage truck, right?

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:53.000
Put on a garbage truck and we were taken to the jail in Hayneville, men on one floor and women on the other floor, and held in the most barbaric conditions that you could imagine.

00:40:53.000 --> 00:41:17.000
With the threats, the women being threatened, especially women with big mouths, who wouldn't shut up seeing, are being raped by the trustees and by the sheriff threatening to have the black men, trustees rape us in the same way that they had been family with Hayneville when she was in jail, not raped ever be her.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:27.000
And the other thing I got very sick in jail, I began to develop an ulcer and my stomach was just on fire.

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:31.000
And I was begging to see a doctor and of course that didn't happen.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:36.000
Jonathan and I were passing notes to each other by then we had become very good friends.

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:44.000
Jonathan was, they were passing, actually I knew Jonathan before that time, I knew him in Selma because we went to my garden together.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:57.000
By that time I felt like if I didn't get out of jail I'm going to die. I felt so sick.

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:16.000
But of course I didn't die. And while Jonathan was in jail, (Robert) Sargent came with Episcopalians to suggest that he could get out of jail, the John refused.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:24.000
When we were finally let out, the jailer just came one day and said, get out of here, you're free.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:36.000
Yes, it scared me to death. Now all of this is instinct. I knew that when people let you out of jail like that, that they've got something planned.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:48.000
Because that's what had happened to Goodman, Chorna. And so I knew instinctively, but I couldn't document it, that something was up.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:57.000
But we went nonetheless with great protests because they said that if we didn't get out of jail once again they started threatening us.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:07.000
I said, this is really a change. People threatening you if you don't get out of jail. Anyway, so we went to the corner store and I've been wrestling with this and I've never said this before.

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:21.000
I've been wrestling with what happened. And one of the things somebody in that group suggested that John, Bob Morris, Joseph, myself wouldn't get so this.

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:30.000
I've been trying to think of that voice recently because I think that's very important.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:40.000
That person not said that we probably would not have gone to that store. Maybe we would have, but I'm not sure we would have gone as a group for the group.

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:53.000
And when we, now Willie Vaughn says that he's something when we were walking to the store, he told us that there was a man with a gun at the store.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:44:03.000
I've been recently trying to figure out if he said that, I don't remember it. And if there was a man at the store and he had been there with the gun, why wasn't he shot?

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:15.000
These are later questions that I'm beginning to ask myself in the last year as I began to understand some of the under dynamics that were happening in the movement that I was not aware of.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:27.000
Will I Vaughn had come to Alabama from Mississippi? Yes. And we got to the store.

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:45.000
And Tom Coleman was standing in the door and he had a gun. And it's one of those moments where you're there, but you're not there.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:59.000
You sort of stopped in your footsteps, but you're trying to figure out how to move. And he said, bitch, because I was in the front. He said, bitch, I'll blow your brains out.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:19.000
And the next thing I knew, I was pulled backwards and I felt literally fell. And Jonathan, I heard a shot and it was Jonathan. He shot Jonathan.

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:27.000
Jonathan never made a sound. I think he was dead instantly or in a coma instantly.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:48.000
Father (Richard) Morrisroe, who was with us, the Catholic priest who had literally just come to South when Martin Luther King issued the call, held on to Joyce Bailey's hands, a local young girl at 17 years old, who was who had been in jail.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:46:13.000
And they were running together. And the next thing I knew, there was another shot. And unlike Jonathan, Father (Richard) Morrisroe began to emit moans and begging for water.

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:36.000
And Joyce Bailey, with some level of consciousness still working, had that way. And when around the in the South, you always have these cars, when around to those empty cars and called my name. And it was when I could hear her that I realized that I was not dead.

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:49.000
And I was surprised to that I thought I was dead. I had no sense that Jonathan was dead. But I got up on my knees, I not got up, I got on my knees and crawled over Joyce.

00:46:49.000 --> 00:47:18.000
And we ran over to the area where the civil rights workers, where the southern freedom workers still remain. And Jimmy Rogers, Gloria Larry, Ruby Sales and Joyce Bailey went back over to try to give Father (Richard) Morrisroe water.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:42.000
And Tom Coleman, like a wild man, was flinging his gun and saying, I'll blow your brains out if we tried to give, if we didn't leave. He let that man lay down there in the hot, all the sun, shot begging for water and threatened to kill anybody who helped him.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:48:09.000
We dispersed and ran in different directions. And somehow I got back to the Freedom House. And when Stokely Carmichael and Silas Norman, who was the project director of Selma, Alabama, when Silas Norman and Stokeley heard what had happened, they went downtown.

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:35.000
And when they got there, the streets were clean. And Jonathan and Father (Richard) Morrisroe were missing. Now, it wasn't a simple thing of knowing where they went. But several days, the SNCC office, Ruby Doris Smith Robinson Robinson tried to find out where they were and nobody would tell us.

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:54.000
So not only was Jonathan dead, he was also missing. And they talked with John Doar of the FBI, I mean of the Justice Department, sorry. And trying to, you can imagine his mother not knowing where he was.

00:48:55.000 --> 00:49:11.000
And finally, they located the morgue where Jonathan was in the hospital where Father (Richard) Morrisroe was. Now, I don't know if you heard the story of Father (Richard) Morrisroe's story.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:40.000
But he was taken to the hospital in a hearse on top of Jonathan's dead body and laid in the hospital hallway for hours before anybody would operate on him until a general, I think, or major in the US Army agreed to take the hospital.

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:46.000
And I wanted to do that.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:50:03.000
So of course, by then, we've got now first real lesson of Southern white murder. And we are young. Nobody's over 22.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:15.000
We are impressionable. We know the horrors of segregation, but we also hopeful. We're also optimistic.

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:34.000
And that's a defining moment, another defining moment. And we were shattered and devastated and trying to make sense out of the loss of our friend John.

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:48.000
And knowing that we had to go to the funeral, but somehow finding it hard to face his mother because he was with us.

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:56.000
We had not done it, but we felt a great responsibility for each other. And so that was very, very hard to do that.

00:50:56.000 --> 00:51:05.000
And of course, my story is known that after that, I just became, went from a big mouth person to someone who rarely spoke.

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:21.000
And I think I spent a great deal of my adult life without even knowing it, trying to find my voice again, trying to be full voice again.

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:37.000
Because I shut down in ways I didn't realize. Like many movement people. And the reason why I shut down is even when I was at Princeton, even when I was at Manhattanville, even when I was out in the world doing peace and justice work.

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:47.000
I never told anybody I'd been in the movement. I never talked about that. So traumatized was I.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:56.000
You went home. Yes. You entered the men back to the table. Yes. Yes.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:52:01.000
What was it you remember here? Is it to your home?

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:14.000
Oh, yes. I remember my visit. My parents were very supportive. And when my mother was hanging out wash one day and some white men came there and told her in the backyard that if I testified, they would kill me.

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:26.000
And despite that, she did not say don't testify. She never said don't testify.

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:31.000
Did anybody from federal law enforcement just found that the eye?

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:34.000
Did you speak to you about going to testify?

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:47.000
I don't remember. I remember John Doar talking about the wills of justice moves very slowly. That's what I remembered out of all of that.

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:53.000
What was your statement when you went back to New England to testify?

00:52:53.000 --> 00:53:02.000
I was frightened but had the resilience of my grandmother and my mother and my father.

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:08.000
And I was determined as much as they didn't want me to testify. I was determined to testify.

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:20.000
And I was also belligerently in the sense that I refused to be intimidated.

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:29.000
I was not going to let her make a verbal fool out of me. The lawyer.

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:49.000
And determined to meet him word for word. And not be afraid even when I walked in the courtroom and this guy made some threat in the courtroom, the hostility hung like icicles in the courtroom.

00:53:49.000 --> 00:54:02.000
So it was not a good place for a young person to be. I was in the face of one of, I understand, the greatest lawyers in Alabama history.

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:22.000
And there I was a child and standing up against those forces and my colleagues standing in the rain all day because they wouldn't allow us to go to the witness room treating us like cattle.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:27.000
And I testified.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:41.000
The comments that I made, no, was not for these, but Shiava attempting to frame your and chocolate and relationship in certain ways in simulated that you were having a sexual relationship.

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:51.000
Well, more, it wasn't a relationship. He insinuated that I was a whore and that Jonathan, like white men in the South, was sleeping with his whore.

00:54:51.000 --> 00:55:09.000
And that the test that Jonathan's character was expressed in the color of the underwear that he wore. I think he wore bright color underwear. And basically he tried to hinge the case around.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:18.000
And ironically, something that the South never wanted to admit but knew that it was there. And that's what he tried to build his case on the unspoken truth.

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:30.000
But of course, Jonathan, I were not having a relationship. Of course, I wasn't a whore. Of course, I was not sleeping in the movement despite the, the, the, the what has later become movement mythology.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:43.000
I was, you know, despite all of my rebellion, I was a woman from Columbus, George, I was in 17 year old. And so I was not from a liberal North where people might do that.

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:51.000
And so it was very shocking, but I was sophisticated enough to know what he was trying to do.

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:59.000
Or even a slipper of hope that the verdict might be related to that. He just considered that a quote on conversation.

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:07.000
I thought that people would act out of it already always acted and I had no evidence that they were going to depart from history.

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:29.000
The sales of, let's this trauma or August and through to the trial.

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:41.000
Was there anything about that experience that caused you to fundamentally reconsider your commitment to the non-violent social protest?

00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:51.000
I had never thought about anything but non-violence. And that remained the same for me. I didn't like killing.

00:56:51.000 --> 00:57:01.000
I, and even when some part of the movement shifted to taking up arms, I was never part of that because the idea of killing was always repugnant to me.

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:15.000
So it reaffirmed the righteousness of non-violence and what happens when you use guns and, and, and other instruments of death.

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:24.000
I could talk about all of the history of the subscribe and in terms of long and complex aftermath.

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:29.000
Maybe we can, we can organize that in a couple of ways.

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:39.000
I just wanted to think about all the implications of the long aftermath through you personally and then also the county and the folks of the county.

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:43.000
Let me start with that second first.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:59.000
You said that killing the women by the moisture of the trial, the equipment, did not affect the people who moved in the county.

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:16.000
No, it did not defeat the movement. You must realize that black people in Lowndes County by virtue of the name Bloody Lowndes had lived with violence, for generations, white violence, and did not and would not give up.

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:32.000
So they, they continued as they had always done and because we were in the middle of movement, further in commitment and a special time in history, the commitment was solidified rather than weakened.

00:58:32.000 --> 00:58:53.000
We had not only the commitment but the collective grief of losing Jonathan, bound us together in the county and instead of retreating because of that, people were even more determined to move forward.

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:56.000
Stoke was even more determined to move forward.

00:58:56.000 --> 00:59:02.000
Salas Norman was even more determined to move forward. I was even more determined to move forward.

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:10.000
So it did not frighten us as it had been, is it intended to do?

00:59:10.000 --> 00:59:16.000
Can you describe the intent of city of an enlargement of 966?

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:38.000
Yes, it was basically ordinary sharecroppers being kicked out of their land for registering to vote and the community decided that even that, which historically might have created a different response, but in this dynamic movement process, they decided that they would make homes,

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:53.000
that they would have 10th city, that they, that they would live in tents and still move forward the movement, that they would not be controlled by economic penalties.

00:59:53.000 --> 01:00:07.000
I think that the whole notion of 10th city that grew up in Washington, DC under Avanathy had its roots in Lowndes County.

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:21.000
The other point that I want to make about this whole 10th city, which is all part of what I call the second indigenous southern freedom movement, the first indigenous movement being runaway slave movement.

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:36.000
And so because it was an indigenous movement, whatever people had, they brought to the table to make 10th city possible and to carry forward the movement.

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:52.000
That could not have happened if just a bunch of people had come in, college students had come in and said they wanted to have a movement and that statement was out of concert with the will of the people and the desire of the people.

01:00:52.000 --> 01:01:21.000
So what was absolutely important about this time was that we were in common accord around a shared vision and that and that vision extended beyond age, beyond class and beyond religious denomination and 10th city survive because the community made it survive.

01:01:21.000 --> 01:01:37.000
But homelessness, the threat of homelessness had always been the threat, whether you were kicked off a plantation, whether you were kicked out of your home, whites had always used this as a means of social control.

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:46.000
So that was very much within the context of that white history of trying to maintain white prerogatives.

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:56.000
And of course, you know, Stoke was very essential to 10th city and people out of 10th city emerged the black Panther symbol, yes.

01:01:56.000 --> 01:02:14.000
And the whole, you know, growing simultaneously was the vision of building another party and being more successful than what had happened with the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party, having learned some important lessons.

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:17.000
I think when you might get 70 when you come into the Alexa Black show.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:19.000
Yes, John, you do it.

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:20.000
Yeah.

01:02:20.000 --> 01:02:25.000
Let me ask about those next couple of years for you.

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:30.000
What, did you like to spend a speaking tour?

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:40.000
No, I was participating in a speaking tour that was at summary thinking early into the fall and then the question was what to do next.

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:46.000
I went down for a little while into Albany and worked with Charles Sherrod.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:49.000
I don't know if you remember that.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:03:08.000
But after everybody left Lauderds County, Stokeley and other people would be essential to the movement, I resettled myself in Washington, D.C. with Gene Wiley and went to New York and lived in James Baldwin's apartment.

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:29.000
He was away for the summer and became very involved with the feminist movement and trying to stay in a college long enough to get my degree, but really expanding my consciousness, not only in terms of the United States, but the global world.

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:41.000
And trying to attend to the deep hurt that I felt around Jonathan's Daniel's death.

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:46.000
And wrestling with the question, how do I wear this label?

01:03:46.000 --> 01:04:02.000
The girl that Jonathan saved with some dignity that did not take away the fact that Jonathan saved my life, but required me to have a life beyond that.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:13.000
For several decades now, you've worked in a range of contexts to do social justice, actually to some of the organizing and educating.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:35.000
I'm only starting to be in the touch on that work. I want to start with, can you talk with about your perspective on the ways that you can hear our team from the museum about civil rights movement projects rather than some freedom of discussion?

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:50.000
I think that I prefer to call it in retrospect the Southern Freedom Movement because it was not only a movement for civil rights, but it was also a movement for human dignity.

01:04:50.000 --> 01:05:01.000
It was also a movement to abolish the violence and terrorism that whites executed against black people for more than 100 years during segregation.

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:18.000
It was also a movement that where we wanted to move from the small spaces that segregation pressed us down into larger spaces that gave us expression, creative, political, and social expression.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:37.000
The reason why I said it was a Southern Freedom Movement on the other hand is that the results of this movement, not only humanized black people, but it had the possibility of opening up the world for white people so that they could lead a more meaningful life.

01:05:37.000 --> 01:05:58.000
The other part about being a movement is that this was not an event. This was a dynamic process that was connected to many events that had happened in the black community like the student movement, the Southern Negro Youth Corruptive in the 1940s.

01:05:58.000 --> 01:06:16.000
We just didn't spring up anywhere and so that the other part about the Southern Freedom Movement is that there was a direct connection between the aims of Southern black education and the ultimate explosion of the Southern Freedom Movement.

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:38.000
I think that when you limit it to civil rights, you obscure. First of all, the horrors of segregation. You do not have to come to terms with the violence, you do not have to come to terms with the economical oppression, you do not have to come to terms with white people who wanted to turn black schools into plantations.

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:52.000
You do not have to come to terms with the fact that no black girl was safe from rape in that society. No black girl was safe from rape in that society. You obscure all of that.

01:06:52.000 --> 01:07:12.000
At the same time, you obscure the long hard years of black struggle and the blood and the sacrifice that we had poured into that struggle. I think that it does not do justice by limit it to, and it is really not accurate to limit it to the movement.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:23.000
One other point I want to make about that is that when we look at Rosa Parks, people often think that she did that because of her civil rights and wanting to sit down on the bus.

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:42.000
But she also did that it was a rebellion of maid, a rebellion of working class women who were tied aboard the bus in Montgomery, the public space, and being assaulted and called out of their names and abused by white bus drivers.

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:59.000
That is why that movement could hold so long. If it had just been merely a protest about riding a bus, it might have shattered. But it went to the very heart of black womanhood and black women played a major role in sustaining that movement.

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:20.000
And so that is why I think it is really important to see the larger context. I don't think a civil rights movement could have lasted as long as this movement did without the culture nuances of God, without the theology, without the intimacy, without the connections, and without the strong desire to be first class human beings.

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:37.000
One I ask about ways in which America's society, black and white, others, the complex communities that human beings in some way can't begin to represent.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:51.000
I think about the way we look back on this history and the way it's written. And I know that you had a very specific kind of experience when you went to graduate school in US history.

01:08:51.000 --> 01:09:05.000
I mentioned you were in your thoughts about the narratives of American history, about the narratives of this period as they were written by professional school beings then and nationally.

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:25.000
Well, I believe that they were narratives of whites dominated the story. And they were narratives that started from a very faulty assumption that black people were second class human beings because they didn't understand that you could be in a school that lacked facilities.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:54.000
You could be in an unjust school, a school system, but that didn't mean that you had a second class mind. They did not understand the roots of nature, the southern culture. And they did not infuse within the narratives, the stories and the work of ordinary people like Vanessa Siddle Walker, a book hellop professor really talks about that black people built this network across region states in the South that connected them.

01:09:54.000 --> 01:10:13.000
That connected them to in a project to advance the black community through education. There is there was very little understanding of black people as having any traits beyond deficits and pathology.

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:29.000
So the argument always started from the deficits and always saw us as the extension of that which white men had made rather than as Ralph Ellison says what we had made out of the ashes of segregation.

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:49.000
And so that was really the problem with the narratives. And oftentimes people who wrote the narratives had very little understanding of the culture that they were writing. For example, they often talked about Martin Luther King being influenced by his time at Crozer and his time at BU.

01:10:49.000 --> 01:11:05.000
And the truth of the matter is while he might have learned a lot there, he knew that in order to be a leader, he had to use what he had grown up with the culture resources. So when he preached, he didn't use the symbols that he had learned at BU.

01:11:05.000 --> 01:11:20.000
He was about God has written a lily of the valley, the bright and morning star, a shelter in the time of storm, He'll make a way out of no way. He was testifying with the people. But historians didn't understand that and they saw him as the exceptional Negro.

01:11:20.000 --> 01:11:49.000
There was no exceptionality in the South, no matter what you accomplish, you were black. Even if you were a college president like Mordecai Wyatt Johnson, you couldn't vote. So the culture of exceptionality did not exist in the South, it existed in the North. Black students were not plucked out of their communities at an early age and put into white schools where they developed a distance and in many ways a contempt for ordinary black people.

01:11:49.000 --> 01:12:08.000
The South was very different. We shared a tremendous intimacy. Nobody talks about that the movement happened because of the intimacy that we shared. No one talks about what did knowing mean in that a Southern freedom culture.

01:12:08.000 --> 01:12:24.000
But very little is understood about that. And I think that we really have to begin to rethink the kind of questions that we ask and the kind of who it is that we use to document what we're saying.

01:12:24.000 --> 01:12:48.000
And why was this movement particularly a Southern movement, not because it was located in the South, not because it was beyond the fact that it was located in the South, it was segregated. It also has to do with the Southern culture that I brought to the movement a certain understanding of the world that was greatly shaped by growing up in the South.

01:12:48.000 --> 01:13:17.000
And then when we reached Bernice Reagon brought to the movement all of what she had learned as a Southern black girl. And that's very important. And that learning kept us despite our disagreements connected to the generations because we sang the same songs and prayed the same prayer. And even when we thought black people were praying too much, our older people were praying too much, we still knew the prayers enough to say amen.

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:25.000
And we kept us connected.

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:46.000
Well, I think what segregation did is that you are bound together and you know each other not only through blood but through the common experience. And the community is a closed society that where you know each other from Columbus, Georgia to Washington, D.C.

01:13:46.000 --> 01:14:03.000
And because black people could not stand hotels, we had to stay with other black people when we traveled. So it was a culture of intimacy where we shared not only the common experience, what we shared the same songs, the same stories, the same relatives.

01:14:03.000 --> 01:14:19.000
We were locked into this intimacy and the intimacy manifested itself where a person could say to you, I'm going to tell your mother if you don't sit down and you sit down because you know she had to catch you to tell your parents that.

01:14:19.000 --> 01:14:28.000
So we were greatly intimate through the school, through the churches, through social clubs, through associations and through the playground.

01:14:28.000 --> 01:14:42.000
The playground has not gotten its place in history about a gathering place that was a training ground for young people to come together. Playground was very essential.

01:14:42.000 --> 01:14:52.000
I'm going to ask about language and two specific instances suggest I think a larger attention to language that you were very close to about.

01:14:52.000 --> 01:15:01.000
At the trial before the defense time, we wanted to refer to a student about a clinic that is next.

01:15:01.000 --> 01:15:10.000
Yes. Another is in graduate school. The principal, you were careful to use the term in slave.

01:15:10.000 --> 01:15:11.000
Yes.

01:15:11.000 --> 01:15:15.000
I thought you were talking a little bit about how you think about that position.

01:15:15.000 --> 01:15:28.000
Well, to the lawyer who wanted to call snake snake, I responded because that was a way of denigrating that he didn't have the intimacy to call snake snake.

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:48.000
That was an intimate term that, and out of respect in this woman setting, he needed to give us the honor of being the student nonviolent coordinating committee and not reduce us to terminology that I felt like he had no right to have access to.

01:15:48.000 --> 01:15:59.000
It was a way of putting him in this place because I thought oftentimes white people want to walk over into culture territories and claim it in ways that they shouldn't.

01:15:59.000 --> 01:16:09.000
In an enslavement, I was a history major in slave reconstruction and abolitionists were my periods.

01:16:09.000 --> 01:16:16.000
And one of the several things, I had just left the South.

01:16:16.000 --> 01:16:23.000
And I knew that black people were not symbols or we could have never had a movement where we changed the South without firing a shot.

01:16:23.000 --> 01:16:36.000
Sambos don't do that. And the other thing is that enslavement almost seemed as if black people passively submitted to being slaves.

01:16:36.000 --> 01:16:43.000
And it didn't say that there was somebody putting them in this place.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:51.000
And so it really obscured the presence and nature of enslavement who was doing it.

01:16:51.000 --> 01:17:02.000
And also when you say master, that's a very benign term that really gives credibility and honor to someone who is an enslaver.

01:17:02.000 --> 01:17:11.000
So I began to really wrestle with those terminologies in the desire to have a true telling of enslavement.

01:17:11.000 --> 01:17:30.000
And I didn't like me at Atlantic passage because it sounded like people went on a vacation and it didn't document brutality, the captivity, the pain, the rate, all of those things that the disassociation never to see your mother again, never to see your grandmother again.

01:17:31.000 --> 01:17:36.000
Never to hear the drums beating in the village, never to hear the sound of your own name again.

01:17:36.000 --> 01:17:48.000
I don't think that was a mid-Atlantic passage. And so I started thinking and I could not have done that had I not been in the movement.

01:17:48.000 --> 01:17:54.000
In 2005, I think thereabouts.

01:17:54.000 --> 01:18:07.000
One thing I want to say about that, one of the things that bothered me about history is that really is there an obvious subject doing the deed.

01:18:07.000 --> 01:18:19.000
And so that you never say white men did this. The only subjects are oppressed people. You say black people, but the white men and subjects are rarely present.

01:18:19.000 --> 01:18:30.000
So you would say the black people were compelled by the institution of slavery, but you never say who compelled them.

01:18:30.000 --> 01:18:43.000
And so that was another thing trying to make people be subject to have some existentialist responsibility for the deeds that they created, which was a tall order at Princeton.

01:18:43.000 --> 01:19:01.000
I want to talk about history and memory and implications of that. In 2005, I think it was you went to the back of the last county for public events.

01:19:01.000 --> 01:19:10.000
When you involved in public events, there were relatively few whites who attended, perhaps almost very few.

01:19:10.000 --> 01:19:13.000
Right.

01:19:13.000 --> 01:19:26.000
And in a prior telling of that, you said a range of very few things about memory.

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:42.000
I think that we live in a society where part of the way that those in power maintain power is through dismembering and revisionist history.

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:54.000
I think that unfortunately we live in an era where even black people suffer from dismembering around the southern freedom movement.

01:19:54.000 --> 01:20:06.000
Because if I can create reality through dismembering, then I can distort who you are and tell you who you are and tell you who you've been with each other.

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:18.000
And only that I can wipe my hands free of the blood. And what, for example, in the people believe that the government gave them jobs when you talk about the southern freedom movement.

01:20:18.000 --> 01:20:30.000
There's no connection between how they got those jobs in the blood and sweat and the constant struggle even up against the government for those jobs.

01:20:30.000 --> 01:20:52.000
And not only that we live in a post-racial world that is tried to wipe out the meaning of whiteness and have distorted the discourse where black people, when we say something is racist, we are the predators and white people are the innocent victims.

01:20:52.000 --> 01:21:16.000
And that comes about because of dismembering and what I call stilling history. Not only because it's not just dismembering when you make yourself the good guy in the story and black people, the villain, and you eradicate our place in history, then you've also stolen history.

01:21:16.000 --> 01:21:28.000
And I think that that has been an important nature of European history and European American history.

01:21:28.000 --> 01:21:43.000
And I also think that without memory you could execute the cultural wars that have been executed in the last 40 years that targeted the strongholds of African American survival.

01:21:43.000 --> 01:21:53.000
Turning liberation theology into black church, a prosperity gospel, tearing down black schools as David Cecelski points out in this book.

01:21:53.000 --> 01:22:18.000
Fragmenting the relationship between black students and black teachers and principals that had been part of the reality for more than 100 years and putting them in classrooms where 85% of the teachers are white in a situation where between 1950 and 1962, 38,000 African American teachers were fired in 13 Southern states.

01:22:18.000 --> 01:22:30.000
All of these actions create dismembering and we are here today because of that dismembering.

01:22:30.000 --> 01:22:43.000
Nobody remembers that Carver High School in 1968 that your my brother graduated had seven national marriage scholars in the segregated school of 200 and some students.

01:22:43.000 --> 01:23:02.000
So what you then say is that black students are criminals, you criminalize black youth and you make the world believe that they are the biggest drug addicts when the statistics show that black, that while we are the largest number in jail, we are not the largest number of users of drugs, white people are.

01:23:02.000 --> 01:23:24.000
And so, and I think in terms of memory, it's important to ultimately remember as it relates to struggle that black people did not come all the way 100 years through the veil of segregation to get one seat in the White House.

01:23:24.000 --> 01:23:45.000
That was not the destination. The destination was to advance democracy in America in a way that not only improve the lives of black people but also the lives of all people in society and we were not wanting to be in a real sense the king.

01:23:54.000 --> 01:24:09.000
And that's a little bit about another issue that we've all witnessed unfold because several decades now it's extraordinary that the jams are acting and everything.

01:24:09.000 --> 01:24:14.000
Yes. And actually, it's about perspective on...

01:24:14.000 --> 01:24:41.000
I think when the discourse shifted in this revisionist climate that criminalized African-American people, most particularly men, I think it opened the door to build the prison and industrial complex because nobody cared that thugs and gangsters

01:24:41.000 --> 01:24:52.000
and people who were not uncivilized people ended up in jail. Nobody even see them as young people. Nobody even see them as people with possibilities.

01:24:52.000 --> 01:25:07.000
So, when the economic system of sharecropping collapsed, white people in the South came up with another system, which is really a plantation system, where these young men are in jail working for major corporations.

01:25:07.000 --> 01:25:21.000
And for sometimes less a dollar a day. And not only that, I see a correlation between the corporation, the coalition.

01:25:21.000 --> 01:25:34.000
Let me just say that I think one of the things that white southerners did through their tax on liberalism and the North was to...

01:25:34.000 --> 01:25:48.000
position their culture, create an environment that positioned the public consciousness to accept southern culture and values.

01:25:48.000 --> 01:26:07.000
And so, agree, materialism, anti-intellectualism, all of the things that held together segregation could not be a true intellectual and really be curious and really a struggle for truth in a punitive segregated society.

01:26:07.000 --> 01:26:18.000
So, that I think that the very things that held together segregation are the things that hold together the prison and industrial complex. And I think not...

01:26:18.000 --> 01:26:35.000
we must understand what happened to the liberal North because the liberal North was also the victim of a cultural war. And the South said we might not want the civil rights of southern freedom movement war, but we darn sure going to win the cultural wars.

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:48.000
And they did. And so, at some point in the 80s, you could hardly make a distinction between a southern politician and a northern politician because they had been galvanized around the same issue of whiteness.

01:26:48.000 --> 01:27:04.000
The other thing that I think is very, very important as we look at this whole conversation of struggle is how do we in the 21st century talk about these human rights issues within our understanding of a technocracy.

01:27:04.000 --> 01:27:13.000
And the understanding of a technocracy where only a few people matter and the rest of collateral damage no matter what the color is.

01:27:13.000 --> 01:27:30.000
So, that's why you have an increase in white poverty. That's why many white males are obsolete in today's world. And instead of understanding technocracy, an anti-human technocracy, they blame other people.

01:27:30.000 --> 01:27:41.000
And they believe that they are in the presence of dangerous black men who pose a threat to the order of society and need to be locked up.

01:27:41.000 --> 01:27:56.000
And they don't have a clue as to this cultural war that has been that raged not only to diminish the gains of the movement, but to destroy the New Deal.

01:27:56.000 --> 01:28:05.000
The gains of the New Deal where Joseph Kennedy, ironically, put a cap on corporate greed in the ways in which they acted in the world.

01:28:05.000 --> 01:28:15.000
Now, it's boundless. It knows no limits. And so that this is, we do not live in a post-racial world.

01:28:15.000 --> 01:28:28.000
We live in a world actually where race and class both are common denominators in ways that they were not earlier because industrialism had brought us faces.

01:28:28.000 --> 01:28:38.000
Technocracy is much more limited. And there is no place for these young men. This is what I'm trying to say. They're meaningless. They're collateral damage.

01:28:38.000 --> 01:28:46.000
And they are considered human waste as (likely) Zygmunt Bauman or Jacques Lacan talks about people being human waste in a technocracy.

01:28:46.000 --> 01:29:03.000
So this is where we are. And that like the South, which was very fascist, because only one voice could go forward, whether it was in the newspaper, whether it was on the public pulpit, we are moving towards that fascist culture.

01:29:03.000 --> 01:29:12.000
And it comes out of the heartbeat of Southern politicians.

01:29:12.000 --> 01:29:20.000
Coalition of Southern people.

01:29:20.000 --> 01:29:29.000
What does something ask you about about spirit housing?

01:29:29.000 --> 01:29:41.000
Spirit house. Yes, which I found that spirit house comes from the understanding that social justice is what we do.

01:29:41.000 --> 01:29:49.000
And forms that we are on the inside and how we live on the outside. And the Greek word was, and so that it's breath.

01:29:49.000 --> 01:29:59.000
And so spirit house is really about how we live, what we take in and what we put out, how we live in relations to each other.

01:29:59.000 --> 01:30:15.000
And in relationship to each other, it is our breath. It is our whole selves integrated and operating in terms of relationality.

01:30:15.000 --> 01:30:28.000
But it's also in a more simpler term is about dealing with issues of education, economics, racial justice.

01:30:28.000 --> 01:30:39.000
And we bring people of all colors together to work on these issues. And right now for the last two years, we have been dealing with the counterculture of education.

01:30:39.000 --> 01:30:49.000
And what might we learn from that counterculture during segregation that would enable black students not to be victims in public schools today.

01:30:49.000 --> 01:31:00.000
And one of the things that disturbed me so tremendously, and this is about narrative again, these Southern black teachers created outstanding students and leaders.

01:31:00.000 --> 01:31:08.000
And many of them still exist. And no one has bothered to ask them, how did you do it?

01:31:08.000 --> 01:31:24.000
What might we learn from you? What were your strategies? How did you deal with complicated situations? How did you invigorate young people to believe that they could make a difference even when the white world said that they couldn't?

01:31:24.000 --> 01:31:43.000
We've been trying to get that conversation on the table. And we've been trying to make a connection between public schooling and the survival of HBCUs, which are many now are being under the gun for being folded into white colleges that are not doing well.

01:31:43.000 --> 01:31:57.000
Many of these white colleges are mere local colleges that once again need resources from black people. So taking black people's resources to enhance white schools.

01:31:57.000 --> 01:32:04.000
Thank you so much for spending this afternoon with us and this really an honor to be with you.

01:32:04.000 --> 01:32:14.000
Thank you very much for being here and it's been great being with both of you.

01:32:14.000 --> 01:32:24.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

